ce:section.ce:para:
HfCDs were synthesized from CA, TU and HfCl4 with the molar ratio of 3:9:1 via pyrolysis. As a control, CDs were prepared in a similar way by using CA and TU as precursors. The morphology and particle size of HfCDs were analyzed by transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and high-resolution TEM (HR TEM). As shown in Fig. 1
                        a, the obtained HfCDs have an average diameter of 3.73 ± 0.62 nm. Fig. 1b indicates that most of HfCDs have lattice structures. Fig. 1c and d shows clear lattice fringes with d-spacing values of 0.28 nm and 0.32 nm, respectively, corresponding to (020) and (002) graphite crystals [45–48]. Energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX) (Fig. S1a
                        ) verifies the successful incorporation of Hf into HfCDs. X-ray powder diffraction (XRD) pattern (Fig. S1b) of HfCDs shows one typical peak at 26° corresponding to interlayer spacing (002) of graphene [49,50], which is consistent with HR-TEM, further confirming that HfCDs have a high-crystalline graphitic structure. The optical properties of HfCDs were evaluated by UV–Vis absorption and photoluminescence (PL) spectra. As shown in Fig. 1e, there are two absorption peaks at 240 nm and 332 nm in the absorption spectrum of HfCDs, which are attributed to the π - π * transition of CC bond and the n - π * transition of CO bond, respectively [51,52]. The emission spectra (Fig. 1f) demonstrate significant excitation-dependent behaviors of HfCDs. Under the excitation of 365 nm, 400 nm and 500 nm, HfCDs can emit blue, green and red light respectively (inset in Fig. 1f), meaning that HfCDs have the characteristics of multicolor luminescence. The photostability of HfCDs was evaluated by PL spectra. As shown in Fig. S1c, the PL intensity of HfCDs maintained almost constant after 30 days, indicating that HfCDs has excellent photostability. The absolute PL quantum yield determined to be 18.4%. The PL decay curve of HfCDs (Fig. S1d) is of the double exponential and the average decay time is 9.18 ns. The above results show that HfCDs have good fluorescence, and could be exploited for fluorescence imaging [53,54].
